Still, that's the way it's always been for quests, progressive raid&#xD;
targets, etc., yet those have obviously been designed with success&#xD;
indicators along the way (e.g. flagging messages, intermediate quest&#xD;
items, NPC dialogue, and so on). How much less satisfying would it be&#xD;
to run around hailing and killing random mobs and NPCs until one day -&#xD;
*poof* - your Epic just appears in your inventory, with no progressive&#xD;
storyline along the way to tell you how and why you got it?&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
&lt;br&gt;&#xD;
I suppose I'm countering, or at least modifying, my own initial concern&#xD;
here, but truthfully, the number of plausible triggers is limited, so&#xD;
it's&#xD;
inevitable that the progression mechanism will be (roughly) known in&#xD;
the community once it's been solved. Dispensing with in-game messages&#xD;
will, at best, leave it open to some minor real world speculation, at&#xD;
the cost of in-game immersion/storyline.&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description>
